Thursday, January 1, 1953

Started off the New Year by writing up the section of the snake-bite chapter on the duration of snake-bite cases, a small part. Not a very fruitful day. Listened to the Rose Bowl Game in the afternoon.

As of this date the snake bite chapter, on which I began to work last March 1, is all finished, except for the present approved treatment. This shouldn't take very long.

Saturday, January 3, 1953

Worked all day on snake-bite treatment. Poor progress.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 08/24/2012 02:47 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:56 PM

Sunday, January 4, 1953

Today I finished the first draft of the snake-bite chapter. Treatment still needs some working over; and the other parts of the snake-bite chapter must have some new items incorporated. It can almost be said that the first draft of the book is completed, and I can now begin the overhauling, chapter by chapter, to include the new material and also the suggestions made by Perkins, Shaw, Schmidt, and Bogert.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 08/24/2012 02:50 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:56 PM

Monday, January 5, 1953

Some field notes from a letter from George R. Stuart, 6308 Murietta Ave, Van Nuys, Calif.

Chionactis in captivity ate Xantusia vigilis.
Chionactis noted climbing in Larrea divaricata.
Chionactis captured west of Soledad Mt, SW of Mojave.
Hypsiglena found in the Santa Monica Mts, just south of Van Nuys.

Thursday, January 29, 1953

In San Francisco
Went to Chickering and Gregory from 9:20 to 9:45, then to a meeting of the Light and Power Council. At Chickering and Gregory again from 2 to 4 discussing business matters.
Stanford Medical Library from 4:15 to 5:40; then to Wormsers for dinner.

Friday, January 30, 1953

Went down to Stanford on the 8:20 train arriving at 9:20. Went to the Library, then had lunch with Dr. Victor C. Twitty; then more library. Picked up a few items, but more were out. Went to the Natural History Museum and talked herps with Myers, Savage, Cliff, and Carvalho. Then to Pally for supper and did some clerical work at the PA Public Library. Caught the Lark at 9:42.

Monday, February 23, 1953

Arrived in New York this morning at 9:30. Went to the American Museum of Natural History at 11 and worked until 4:30, on bibliographic items. Had lunch with Bogert and Oliver. In addition saw Max Hecht, Geo. Haas of Jerusalem University, Carl Koopinan, Carl Gans, and Sam McDowell.

Page Edit History:
  • Awramj 08/25/2012 11:35 PM

Tuesday, February 24, 1953

Worked today at the New York Public Library from 9:15 to 5:00 with only a few minutes for lunch. Did quite well clearing up bothersome items. Had dinner with Kittridges and Allen Heyneman.

Friday, February 27, 1953

Arrived at Chicago at 9:30. Was at Crerar Library from 10:15 to 1:20 and at Newberry Library from 1:30 to 2:40. Crerar was fruitful; Newberry poor.
Conferred with Uhlendorf and Kellogg from 2:50 to 5:10 on various matters, particularly the atomic energy project.
Left for home at 7 PM on the Super Chief.

Sunday, March 1, 1953

Arrived at San Bernardino at 7:03. Drove to San Diego arriving at 9:30. It was cold and rainy. Spent the afternoon catching up, including 2 hours at the office. Brattstrom and his wife called late in the afternoon.

Saturday, March 21, 1953

Sunday, March 22, 1953

Spent the morning finishing the preparation of a copy of the snake-bite section (Symbol 13) to be sent to Bogert and [Oliver. This section is now completely up-to-date with the most recent new data all incorporated.
Spent the afternoon and evening working on (symbol) 5 and (symbol) 6, Populations and Ecology. I can see that these are going to be tough, not only because of the quantity of new material available, but also because some rearrangement and co-ordination is necessary.

Thursday, April 2, 1953

Jack Mac Neil's collecting
Total mileage night driving 146

April 2
8:12 Desert longnose 71 degrees 13" Rocky and brushy desert. 3 mi. S. of Borrego.

The continual practicing was very tiring, but there was much of interest and novelty in the methods used. The actual show ran from 7:00 to 7:30; was on venomous snakes, and seemed to go off in a satisfactory manner.

Saturday, May 30, 1953

Brattstrom called this morning. Besides his fossil cave rattler from California, he has 2 from Florida, 1 a full species, the other a subspecies of adamanteus. He says Lowe and Norris' Enyo paper is still delayed. He will send me something on rattler phylogeny based on osteology withing a few months, but his main thesis wont appear for several years.

Worked on miscellaneous catching up in the morning; then got back to the revision of Control.

Sunday, July 12, 1953

Made better progress today. Woke up at 3:30 and by 7:30 had read and corrected the new material written yesterday. Then worked on length and body proportions until 8:30, after which I was too bushed to do more. Finished length and almost completed body proportions.

The overhauling of this section is different from the rest; much more a matter of bringing statistics, proportions, and curves down to date, rather than inserting new bibliographical references. This makes it much slower than the other types of revision.

Wednesday, July 22, 1953

Left for the north on the 12:45 train. At the LA Public Library from 4-6 but got almost nothing cleared up. Caught the Owl to SF at 9.

Page Edit History:
  • Awramj 08/30/2012 09:28 PM

Thursday, July 23, 1953

First went to Chickering and Gregory and saw Sherman Chickering and Pattee. then to the Light and Power Council from 10 until 2:10. At the Stanford Medical Library from 3 until 3:30, and at the SF Public Library from 4 to 5:30. Cleared up a few items but not very much. Left heel bothering; didn't sleep too well. Was at the Palace.

Page Edit History:
  • Awramj 08/30/2012 09:31 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:56 PM

Friday, July 24, 1953

Key System strike this morning so had to take a taxi to Berkeley. At U.C. at 8:20. Waited until 10:30 to see August Fruge - the manager of the U.C. Press and talked to him and his new science editor Littell (?) until 11:20 about a combined sponsorship with the Zoo of the rattler book. The discussion covered many aspects of the proposal. Left with them a table of contents and the introduction. Will send them a couple of additional chapters and then there will be further discussions.

Went up to MVZ and saw Stebbins, Gorman and others. Also saw Cook's Scutulatus (female) - Oreganus (male) hybrids. Worked in the main and biological libraries from 12:45 until 4:50 and cleared up quite a few items.

Stebbins drove me from Berkeley to the SP Depot at 1st and Broadway in Oakland. Had supper at the Bow & Bells on the Estuary and caught the Oakland Lark at 8:43. Heel very painful all day and a particular nuisance because of the strike and no taxis.

Page Edit History:
  • Awramj 08/30/2012 09:40 PM

Saturday, July 25, 1953

Came down on the 9:10 train. Went to a Zoo director's meeting from 12:30 to 3:00. Told them about the U.C. Press meeting yesterday.

Spent the afternoon and evening catching up.

The heel was very bothersome and almost caused me to miss my train.

Page Edit History:

Sunday, July 26, 1953

Worked hard today from 7 AM to 10 PM to make up for an otherwise unfruitful weekend. Worked on genetic correlations in scalation and in length-scale correlations. It was necessary to recalculate several scale averages -- very time consuming -- and re plot 6 scatter diagrams, which were finished. Almost completed this part of (Section) 9.

Heel much better today.

Cocktail party 6-8. Then worked until 9:30. Tired out. A poor day with the hybrids still unfinished.

Tuesday, September 1, 1953

Left for the north with GG at 3 PM. Arrived at Santa Barbara at 9:15 PM. Put up at the Casa del Mar Auto Court. 220 miles.

Page Edit History:
  • Awramj 08/30/2012 10:34 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:56 PM

Wednesday, September % 1953

Left Santa Barbara this morning at 8:30 and arrived at Palo Alto at 7:00 PM. Took a roundabout road. First went to Lompoc to see the cultivated flowers, and then to Cayucos to buy a soup tureen, but Mills the owner of the antique shop wasn't around. Went over the hills to Paso Robles on a narrow road. It was very hot in the Salinas Valley. Saw the Johns Manville diatonite mine at Lompoc, but didn't attempt to go in.

1 striped racer seen alive in the road 5 miles north of Lompoc, Santa Barbara County, the only reptile seen on the entire trip. Brush. No chance to catch him. 364 miles today.

Page Edit History:
  • Awramj 08/30/2012 10:39 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:56 PM

Thursday, September 3, 1953

At the Stanford Museum today from 10 to 11. Saw Myers, Margaret Storey, Banta, Savage and others. The recent Orca expeditions got 2 rattlers at islands where none had been reported before! an atrox from San Pedro Martes (the one I had already seen) and a queer item, probably a new species or subspecies from Santa Catalina. Unfortunately the head is in bad shape so that it is difficult to make much out of it on a preliminary examination. The rattle is just a blunt nubbin. Looks like a west San Joaquin Oreganus, but is probably nearer to lucasensis than anything else. The tail bands are scute type.

Worked at the Stanford Library from 11:40 to 1:25 and cleared up a few items.

Arrived at Sacramento at 6:00. Went via Golden Gate Bridge and Black Point. 174 miles today. At the Hotel Senator.

Page Edit History:
  • Awramj 08/30/2012 10:46 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:56 PM

Friday, September 4, 1953

At a meeting of the California State Chamber of Commerce all morning and at noon. W.C. Mullendore talked on the recent Edison strike at lunch meeting.

At the State Library from 1:30 to 4:45 and cleared up several items.

Left for Berkeley at 12:00 and arrived at 3:30 at the Silva Motel, and new place and very pleasant. Miles 81

Monday September 7, 1953

Tuesday, September 8, 1953

Spent most of the day at U.C. at the Main Library from 9:30 to 12:00; and 3:50 to 5:15; the biology library from 1:35 to 2:15, and cleared up quite a few items. Had lunch with Littell from 12:30 to 1:30 and discussed the publication problem at some length. He said the people in the U.C. Press were favorably disposed, but the decision would rest with the publication committee which would meet late in September. Meanwhile, additional sections are to be sent up for examination.

Spent an hour with Stebbins and his associates. Saw some pricai recently collected in Sinaloa and Durango. Also a leafnose from 13 mi. SSW of Boulder City, Nev., with only 30 blotches on the body (not including the tail).

Saturday, December 19, 1953

In the morning worked on back sections of Section 7 Bodily Functions, re checking.

Also went to a Zoo board meeting at noon, and went over the first 2 sections or parts of Section 7 with Perkins to get his and Shaw's suggestions. This took until 4 P.M. Spent the rest of the day on Section 7 incorporating changes.

Sunday, December 20, 1953

Got back on the beam today and progressed with the coordination of sections 5 and 6 (Populations and Habitats) a difficult problem. Then worked on swimming and tree-climbing, items formerly in Section 6 and now to be transferred to Section 7. Completed the first draft of the revisions of these two subjects. Better progress today than for some time in the past.

Saturday, December 26, 1953

Today made a good start on the combining of old sections 5 and 6. Worked especially on altitudes and island populations. Got rather badly slowed down in the afternoon.

Out to dinner at the Kona Kai Club in the evening with the Gould-Lawson tribe.

Page Edit History:
  • Awramj 09/13/2012 10:17 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:56 PM

Sunday, December 27, 1953

Brattstrom called today. He has one paper almost finished completely summarizing the fossil rattlesnakes. Will describe a new extinct subspecies of adamanteus and another new extinct species, both from Florida.

Asked him to do what he could to push publication of a summary of rattler skulls and vertebra. This is his doctorate thesis; must get permission of his committee to do so.

Worked long hours today and made considerable progress combining Section 5 and Section 6 and rewriting them.

Page Edit History:
  • Awramj 09/13/2012 10:20 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:56 PM

Monday, December 28, 1953

Page Edit History:
  • Awramj 09/13/2012 10:21 PM

Tuesday, December 29, 1953

Page Edit History:
  • Awramj 09/13/2012 10:21 PM

Wednesday, December 30, 1953

Page Edit History:
  • Awramj 09/13/2012 10:21 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:56 PM

Thursday, December 31, 1953

This was my last day as Chairman of the Board and Chief executive officer of the San Diego Gas and Electric Co after 43 years with the company. I shall continue in a consulting capacity as a member of the board of directors, executive committee and finance committee.

I hope to get along faster with my herpetological projects, especially the completion of the rattlesnake book. I have no regrets at quitting at age 70; I have no worries as to keeping busy, the trouble with so many retired people. There will be no let down for me.

At the Cavarrees for a New Years' party tonight. Out late.

Page Edit History:
  • Awramj 09/13/2012 10:25 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:56 PM
